Pulmonary Kaposi's sarcoma presenting as fulminant respiratory failure.
 A 32-year-old black man, a homosexual patient with a history of lymphadenopathy, presented with diarrhea, weight loss, and a bilateral interstitial infiltrate.
 Within days after admission, the patient developed dyspnea with rapid progression to respiratory failure and a rapid increase of the infiltrate.
 An open-lung biopsy showed Kaposi's sarcoma.
 Treatment with chemotherapy reversed the respiratory failure.
